DataElement.preferredDefinition: The laboratory result in nanogram per milliliter (ng/mL) of a glycoprotein hormone that is synthesized by the thyroid follicular cell and is incorporated, by peptide bonds, with thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). Thyroglobulin levels serve as a tumor marker for monitoring the status of differentiated thyroid carcinomas.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Information related to the laboratory result of a glycoprotein hormone that is synthesized by the thyroid follicular cell and is incorporated, by peptide bonds, with thyroid hormones (T3 and T4).  Thyroid hormone release occurs when T3 and T4 are enzymatically split from thyroglobulin.  Thyroglobulin levels serve as a tumor marker for monitoring the status of differentiated thyroid carcinomas.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A procedure for critical evaluation; a means of determining the presence, quality, or truth of something.

Concepts.definition: Any procedure that involves testing or manipulating a sample of blood, urine, or other body substance in a laboratory setting.

Concepts.definition: Thyroglobulin (2768 aa, ~305 kDa) is encoded by the human TG gene. This protein is involved in thyroid hormone synthesis.

ValueDomain.preferredName: Laboratory Test Result Nanogram Per Milliliter Value
ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: A laboratory result using the metric measure of nanograms per milliliter (ng/mL)._A metric unit of mass equal to 10E-9 gram, or one millionth of a milligram._A measure of volume for a liquid.  A milliliter is approximately 950 times smaller than a quart and 30 times smaller than a fluid ounce.  A milliliter of liquid and a cubic centimeter (cc) of liquid are the same.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: the results of evaluations of the patient and the patient's disease.

The metric unit of mass equal to one billionth of a gram (10E-9 gram) or one thousandth of a milligram.

A unit of volume equal to one millionth (10E-6) of a cubic meter, one thousandth of a liter, one cubic centimeter, or 0.061023 7 cubic inch. A cubic centimeter is the CGS unit of volume.
